USA: Repeating is the mother of wisdom
It is funny how Barack Obama, the president with the cleverest reputation, has repeated the strategy of his predecessor, who he himself considered to be the stupidest, on the Afghan question.
When he finally sweaty his desired Afghan doctrine, it turns out he copied it through a copy of Bush's Iraqi script three years ago.
Not only is he using "as in Iraq" word turnover several times in the text itself, but he did not hesitate to even use the title of the Bush Declaration of January 2007 as the title of his own declaration: "A new way forward."
Three years ago, he himself criticised Bush's idea of sending fresh military reinforcements to Iraq, plagued by civil war, as "irresponsible, and in its aftermath, catastrophic decisions."
But the following months have shown that Bush's strategy, based on the recommendations of field leaders, was the only possible and highly successful one so much that news stories about Iraq are not being discussed at all today.
It did not improve Bush's reputation, but objectively left his successor a much more grateful starting point than could be expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will repeat itself.
He was asked to increase the military contingent once again by field commanders, especially the head of Afghan operations, General Stanley McCristal, who even, despite the subordination practices, severely criticized the hesitant gunmen in the White House.
He asked 40,000 men to break things for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but it was the best he could do, so at least he cheated the general out of 10,000 soldiers.
He was able to squeeze the promise of another 5,000 out of Europe, even though he originally counted at least 10.
The most problematic thing about the entire Obama strategy seems to be his intention to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and to end this process in three years. The entire Obama doctrine raises more questions than it provides answers.
Many doubt that half-price increases will give the same fruit as Iraq's progress.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraq's society is relatively well organized, its leaders honor agreements.
The Afghan situation is characterised by the opposite symptom - no one can be relied on and no agreements are adhered to.
Under these conditions, Afghan security forces are poorly prepared to change the master every day according to how convenient it is for them.
Political institutions, even if formally established, will remain but a pohomkin village for which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to grow.
The balancing of the interests of various ethnic groups is extremely difficult, given the lack of clarity of the circumstances that complicate Pakistan and Iran's influence even more.
Nor does the construction of a "capable state," which is the minimalist objective of the entire operation, seem too realistic.
The time horizon of Obama's strategy captures its voluntarism.
In the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only deteriorated and is now on the verge of an explosion.
Believing that soldiers sent into war with the purpose of "early return home" will bring about a miracle, only a soul can truly be romantic, untouched by reality.
From a political point of view, setting the date of withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible, as the Taliban will see this as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The last NATO summit has shown that Europeans' willingness to participate in combat operations in Afghanistan is coming to a close.
European politicians do not know, nor do they want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is linked to the war at the foothills of Hindu Kush.
Another factor able to intervene radically in the situation is the development of events around Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the intensified sanctions against Iranians do not take effect, there will be a difficult question before the United States whether to try to solve the problem with military force.
It will need to be answered at a time when, according to Obama, America will move on to the winning withdrawal from Afghanistan.
But any such solution will also mean a dramatic turn in the Afghan situation.
The only patch for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left in the presidential election, and therefore enough time remains to come up with another strategy if it proves to be a total failure.
