Czech discovery: a substance that also works on 'hardened' HIV viruses
A team of Czech and German scientists are testing new compounds that can slow the spread of the HIV virus in the organism.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works on viruses that have already acquired immunity against medicines.
This in some cases outweighs the fact that the compound does not act as strongly on the normal variant of the virus as some medicines already available.
AIDS disease can't be cured yet.
However, a combination of medicines that prevent HIV virus from multiplying in the body may significantly prolong patients' lives.
However, their use is accompanied by a number of side effects.
In addition, the incomplete suppression of virus multiplication results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which medicines are no longer effective.
The work of experts from the three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, from VŠCHT Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with virus resistance.
They have shown that substances called metalocarbonates act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalocarbonates are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a different way than all medicines used today, so they can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists come up with new "improved" compounds prepared based on knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the viral protein.
Metalocarbonates have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-wall cages made up of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Traitorous and resistant virus
HIV protease is an HIV protein that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease caused by HIV fission, mature viral particles would not have occurred.
When we stop HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, and scientists explain in the press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medical Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic chain, which is further systematically amended.
A little weaker but more reliable
