A speech from Oslo: "just war" has earned Obama praise from the right.
On Friday, the American right welcomed Barack Obama's speech the day before in Oslo, satisfied that the Nobel Peace Prize winner for 2009 defended the concept of a "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
Conservatives who initially mocked the award to Obama on October 9, this time applauded the presidential speech, including Sarah Palin, a former candidate for the Vice President in the 2008 election.
I liked what he said, Palin, the muse of the right-wing Republican, said to the US Today newspaper, and added that she herself expressed the "sometimes necessary" wars in her memoirs that are currently coming out.
War is, of course, the last thing Americans would want to do, but it is necessary.
All terrorists must be detained there, he believes.
President Obama, who inherited two wars in Afghanistan and Iraq after his predecessor George W. Bush, justified the deployment of forces on Thursday in Oslo and used his speech to clarify his decision to send another 30,000 troops to Afghanistan nine days before that.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, assessed that the President did a "very good job" in Oslo.
I think the speech was really very good, congratulated the former President of the House of Representatives, who particularly appreciated the President's mention of "the existence of evil in the world."
In a way, I considered this speech quite historic, said Gingrich during the interview on "The Takeaway."
The former Member, whom some consider to be a possible Republican candidate in the 2012 presidential election, was thrilled to see the "left-wing president" to remind the Nobel Committee members of the Nobel Prize, "that they themselves would not be free to pass on the peace prize if the use of forces did not exist."
According to Michael Gerson, former author of the speeches by George W. Bush, now editor of the Washington Post, Obama presented "a very American speech."
Not only did he introduce himself as a "world citizen" as always, but "spoke like the US President" and reminded Europeans "that they live in a safe bubble that they did not create themselves, and that they do not do too much to preserve it," Gerson assessed.
Among the few discontent of the right are the Hawks of the Bush era, the former UN ambassador John Bolton, who described the speech as "monotonous, pompous and without inspiration," as stated on the National Review Online website.
On the left of the president, for example, the democratic representative Dennis Kucinich is appalled at the view of Barack Obama, how he justifies the use of force.
"If we wrap war in the cover of justice, we can easily justify the massacre of innocent people," he warned.
However, the medium-left press takes a commendable view of the President.
Although the Los Angeles Times continues to regard the award of peace to Obama as premature, he assessed his performance as "overperformance," even for a speaker known for his talents.
The Oslo speech should serve as a guide to international decisions in conflict resolution, in the fight against poverty and oppression, "says the California daily with passion.
Obama "gave the speech as needed," evaluated the New York Times, and called it "simple and enlightening."
