Turkey's justice has dissolved for the Kurdish party, and this decision bears heavy consequences.
On Friday, the Turkish Constitutional Court decided to abolish the main pro-Kurdish party in the country. This decision immediately provoked protest demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the south-east of the country and Istanbul.
This decision may greatly complicate the task of a government that seeks to give the Kurdish community a friendly hand in trying to end 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society Party (DTP) has been dissolved because it has become "a nest of activities threatening the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," said the President of the Supreme Court, Hasim Kilic, after four days of negotiations.
The decision was taken unanimously by 11 judges, when the majority-seven votes were needed for the dissolution of the party, said Kili, and added that 37 party cadres, including President Ahmet Türk and MEP Aysela Tugluk, were banned from taking part in political life for five years.
At the same time, the judge announced the abolition of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr Türk and Mrs Tugluk and the confiscation of the party's assets by the Ministry of Finance.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (500).
The party's leadership had already pointed out before the verdict that Members would rather leave Parliament than act as Members without political jurisdiction.
The decision is a continuation of the process initiated in 2007 by the Prosecutor of the Court of Cassation, Abdulrahman Yalcinkay, who accuses the DTP of obedience to the "orders" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), which Ankara and many countries consider to be a terrorist organisation.
Many observers believe that DTP is the legal political display of the rebels of the PKK.
The party assures that it has no "basic link" with the PKK, but refuses to designate it as a terrorist organisation and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The verdict of the court comes at a time when the government is giving the Kurdish community a friendly hand and offers a number of measures to strengthen their rights and try to limit the support of the Kurds towards the PKK and thus end the conflict.
The DTP leadership has confirmed that the dissolution of the party could lead to a resumption of tensions in south-east Anatolia, where many demonstrations have been reversed in recent weeks against the conditions under which the leader of PKK Abdullah Öcalan is being held in conflict with the police.
Since the justice decision was announced, thousands of demonstrators have gathered outside the DTP's headquarters in Diyarbakir, a large city in the southeast, which is mainly populated by Kurds.
The police used tear grenades and water cannons, protestors threw Molotov cocktails or shot slingshot stones.
Also in Istanbul, about a hundred people demonstrated.
After the verdict, Mr Türk stated that the decision of justice would only "deepen despair."
Turkey cannot resolve this question (Kurds, note.) by banning the party, declared it in the press.
The government, made up of a party from the Islamist movement, also condemned this decision.
We are by principle against the interference of the parties.
The Minister for Energy said Taner Yildiz.
This decision is a complete outburst of democratic proposals launched by the government, commented by the political scientist Ahmet Insel.
Of course we can look forward to the reaction from PKK, he added.
On Thursday, PKK signed up for one of the most murderous attacks in the north of Turkey, which killed seven soldiers three days earlier.
