Dinosaur cradle
Tawa hallae looked like a lot of other carnivorous dinosaurs: An animal two metres long and 1.50 metres tall ran on two strong back legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short anterior legs with sickle claws and a long tail.
If this species lived a few million years later, it would be nothing special.
Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in Thursday's edition of Science magazine wrote that Tawa hallae was but one of the first dinosaurs with these bodily traits.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in today's New Mexico, which was then in the equatorial dry area of the supercontinent Pangea.
Tawa opens a new window to the earlier evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He's showing us a lot about kinship, enlargement, and early dinosaur signs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began digging up Ghost Ranch in the north of New Mexico.
Sometimes on one day we found a dozen dinosaur bones, which is unprecedented for triassic deposits, informing team member Randall Irmis of the Museum of Natural History in Utah.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by scientists as a new species.
During the dig, they collected the remains from a total of five individuals.
The discovery confirms the theory of the early history of dinosaurs.
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it's an unusual find: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are very rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not share this enthusiasm without reservation.
This find is not particularly sensational, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current scientific opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But a lot of the oldest fossils are not complete, which is why the assignment of the pradinosaurs is usually questionable.
For example, experts discuss when lizards were divided into the three most important development lines: carnivorous teropods, which later included Tyrannosaurus rex, Velociraptor and also birds, "long-necked" four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and herbivores Ornithischia (birds), such as Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
Tawa hallae is the original terrace after analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues.
It shows an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, researchers found, for example, evidence of air bags that even the offspring of teropods have birds.
Thanks to air bags, bird breathing is more effective than mammals.
At Tawa Hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive teropod with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of huge sauropods later also had air bags and light bones, this useful innovation was probably already created by the common ancestor of both groups.
At least three migratory waves to North America
Because so far known as the most primitive dinosaurs lived in South America, scientists concluded that the lizards were there for the first time.
According to this, three lines of development were divided soon and spread from South America to all continents, which at that time, as the supercontinent Pangea formed a single Earth mass.
The fact that the team found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related, teropods, along with Tawa hallae would speak for that.
The three of them can't come from one common, migrated ancestor, they argue scientists.
We believe there have been at least three migratory waves to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of a scientific study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to the group of the heaviest dinosaurs, lived in Poland today, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His conjecture could put together a distorted picture, because very many primitive fossils of dinosaurs have been preserved in South America, and they are rarely found on other continents ever.
As the dinosaurs proved, from a relatively rare by-line of reptiles to the ruling vertebrates on earth in the Middle Ages, it remains a puzzle.
During the trias, dinosaurs shared their living space with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today's crocodiles and flying lizards and countless other lizards.
Around the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread around the world and developed many new species, while relatives died out and the interface of the Triassic and the Jurassic.
The history of success didn't last forever.
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been mass extinction, which dinosaurs happened to survive, but not reptiles.
Or the dinosaurs were better adjusted, so they could push out the competition.
In any case, the history of success did not last forever.
150 million years later, the meteor hit helped another group of animals, who also evolved into a triassic and have lived in the shadow of mammals ever since.
