75% of working mothers have maternal-related work problems.
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who intend to have a child.
This is the result of the study 'Fertility and the career of Spanish women' carried out by the CSIC in cooperation with the Institute of Women.
The study was attended by 9.737 women aged 15 to 75 and the results are clear: 75% of working mothers have limited labour market opportunities due to maternity.
The study underlines that at the beginning of cohabitation there are many differences in opinion of the number of children depending on whether they are working or not and also on the type of employment.
Women who do not work away from home, work part-time or have a stable job, start living with their partner sooner, give birth to their first child and have more children overall.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, especially in the public sector, cohabitation and motherhood are postponed, and have fewer offspring.
"Women aged 35 to 49 with stable employment have their first child on average 3.7 years from the beginning of cohabitation with a partner. This figure is 4.1 for women who have devoted a greater part of their life to achieving their stable employment and have therefore had to postpone cohabitation and the arrival of children.
The type of profession also has a strong influence on motherhood, although less influence on the time of starting coexistence with the partner, "explains Margarita Delgado, who is engaged in research at CSIC.
Another factor affecting the age of women at the time of marriage and the birth of the offspring is the degree of education.
Research shows that the higher the degree of education, the higher the age when women get married and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in an age group of 35 to 49 years, women with basic and higher education gave birth to their first child at the age of 25.1 or 32.1.
"There is another difference between women depending on their level of education.
Women with basic education get married and give birth to their first child before they find a stable job, while women with middle or high education go the other way and prefer to have a stable job, before marriage and the birth of their first child, "Delgado says.
