The handbrake auxiliary system is already mandatory equipment.
As in the case of the ABS anti-lock system, even with ESP stability control, auxiliary manual brake systems, all of this will become mandatory equipment for European cars.
In fact, it is already part of the mandatory equipment of all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for others the deadline for the removal of the deficiency is set, which is February 2011.
The measure introduced in the EU aims to increase the protection of pedestrians, while operating in such a way that it can help prevent many collisions.
The auxiliary manual brake system increases the brake pressure in an emergency, which will be detected by the system after the driver has stepped on it.
But he can't always keep this pressure to the end.
According to a study conducted by Bosch car parts manufacturer, a third of the drivers who are in an accident did not press the brake before the collision and half of them did not use the full force of the brake.
Up to 1.100 accidents
On the contrary, this assistance requires the maximum possible from the braking system, reducing the braking distance of the vehicle.
According to a study carried out in the EU itself, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of device, up to 1 100 fatal accidents per year related to pedestrians could be avoided.
The reduction of this number will be even more notable - according to calculations would prevent one of the four accidents affecting persons - after the introduction of so-called intelligent manual brake systems.
In this case, vehicles will be equipped with a system that captures obstacles (using radar or camera) and reports them to the driver, except for light braking.
If the driver responds, it will help to increase the pressure on the pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond, even if the collision cannot be prevented, the device will apply as intensely as possible to the brake and reduce the risk of damage to a minimum.
